<br>
First, The class only starts to run into balance issues once we hit level 34 or so, and goes until level 44.  For those ten levels, you can't do enough damage to most Kunark mobs to satisfy the design of the class.  This means we can't do the damage we need to do to do &quot;massive damage&quot; to mobs, and actually do less than many classes.<br>
<br>
Second, from 44 through 50, we are only average for damage output compared with the melees that are running around with items that drop in Old Sebilis and Howling Stones.  We CAN do well in this range, but it's from knowing how to play the class and use the abilities we are given in ways not planned by Verant, not based on the strength of the class itself.  In other words, quad kiting, using rains on single mobs even though they are an AoE type of spell, etc.<br>
<br>
From 51 through 54, this is where most start to get the +mana items we need in order to do well with our class.  The +5 damage/level/cast going from 51 upward is too weak to stand on it's own, and you feel like you just can't keep up with the damage done by the melees with that good equipment.   The way to test this is take a corpse(any corpse), and with a full bar of mana, begin casting draught spells.  How many casts do you get on a full bar of mana.  With fizzles pulling mana, you will get an idea how much damage you will be able to do if resists arn't counted.<br>
<br>
At 55 and going up, the new items you have managed to pick up will finally start to be felt.  At 56 I am able to do 13 casts(without resists) of our draught spells.  This doesn't count resists, but it's a decent number of casts, and this doesn't include mana regen since it was chaincast with no flowing thought items, and no clarity or mana song.  This really isn't bad for damage output since we almost never should cast off a full bar of mana in that way.<br>
<br>
<br>
So, do we suck as a class?  Hell no.  But can our class abilities keep us powerful without a lot of learning?  No, and that's the problem.  Almost all classes out there can take an unskilled player, and still make the class workable.  An ebayed warrior may not be as good as having a skilled player behind the character, but can still be considered a strong asset.  The same with clerics, and to a smaller degree enchanters, and most of the other classes.  Wizards are the ONLY class that can't do our job based on the power of the class itself, and we feel it.  Doing snares, stuns, nukes, knowing when to overburn to pull a mob off the enchanter or cleric, knowing how to nuke without getting TOO badly agroed so the tanks can't get the mob off you.<br>
<br>
  Those are the skills that make a wizard a very useful addition to groups, but since it IS a learned skill, we need to prove ourselves to be skilled to everyone who doesn't know us.  Knowing the abilities of others in the group is also key to playing our class well, which is why we have difficulties in pickup groups.  If you play with guild members a lot, you get to know how much damage they can do in a given period of time, so you time your casts around the damage of others.  In a pickup group, you don't know, so it's easy to make mistakes while you start to remember that not every rogue has their epic, and not every warrior has a decent damage output(many melees out there DO have really bad equipment).  Because of this, even the best wizard will have bad days when dealing with pickup groups, which hurts the reputation of the wizard class even more.<br>
<br>
So, that's my interpretation of the problems with the wizard class.  It's not that the class sucks, the problem is that the class doesn't stand on it's own strength the way all the others do.<br>
